When I was Lt. Governor, I’d say the job was like being invited into MN’s living room. Now I want to return the favor. My office might not be as cozy as a living room, but I want to be sure that when you’re traveling to our nation’s capital, you can still get a big MN welcome.
And to that, I want to announce that each Wednesday morning when the Senate is in session, I’m opening my office—309 Hart Senate Building—for coffee and conversation starting at 9 AM.

When I’m not traveling around Minnesota meeting you (my favorite part of the job, by the way), I’m in Washington, fighting for what matters to our state. If you’re ever out here for a visit, I urge you to drop by my office and say hi.

My bill addresses an anti-competitive loophole that big pharmaceutical companies exploit in order to force Americans into buying overpriced drugs.

Since becoming Senator, I’ve traveled around MN to talk w/ families, seniors, & communities. In these conversations, the topic of high prescription drug prices almost always comes up. The amount of $ Minnesotans are paying for their medications is out of control & unsustainable.
My bill takes aim at a big pharma tactic that keeps affordable generic drugs out of the hands of Minnesota families and seniors.

I’m proud to announce that just a few hours ago, I introduced my first bill since in the Senate: the Expanding Access to Low Cost Generic Drugs Act, designed to help lower the cost of prescription drugs.

#NetNeutrality fuels this kind of entrepreneurship. It’s good for business and education, for communities, and for the freedom to access information without having to pay an extra toll.

Because that farmhouse was connected to the internet—and bc #NetNeutrality put him on a level-playing field w/ big businesses across the US—he could compete with anybody. & at the end of the day, he could walk out to the driveway & meet his kids when they came home from school.
The dad—who works in finance—not only needed access to the internet, but he also had to be able to make transactions and keep a pulse on the financial world.

Let me give you an idea why #NetNeutrality matters to me. And why it should matter to you, as well. A while back, I met a family who moved from the Twin Cities to Fergus Falls to live at their family farmhouse. https://t.co/I7q8UTpTcs

Today I’m joining my colleagues in Congress, tech companies, grassroots organizations, and advocates to speak out in support of restoring the #NetNeutrality protections that millions of Americans fought to establish. Watch live: https://t.co/giOMWvGa9x

#Netneutrality—the principle that what we read, view, and watch on the internet can’t be slowed down or sped up by deep pocketed corporations. It’s what allows the website for your local brewery in Northern Minnesota to be on the same playing field as the big guys.

I’m deeply concerned by President Trump’s proposal to eliminate #LIHEAP—a program that helps seniors, veterans, and families keep their homes warm during particularly cold winter months. All told, it helps cover 126,000 Minnesota households.
In states like Minnesota, where the temperature regularly drops below zero, having a warm home isn’t an option—it’s a necessity.

text:
This weekend I’m traveling around the state for the first time as U.S. Senator to talk with Minnesotans about issues that matter to them. Here’s a snapshot of my travels so far:

https://t.co/tsoVPsTJKX

In a world of innovation, Minnesotans must have access to #broadband, and I’m going to push for more investment to level that playing field and to make sure that all of Minnesota’s broadband needs are met. Because if you aren’t connected, you aren’t competing.

I’m in Mountain Iron because I want to hear directly from local leaders and advocates about #broadband issues in northeastern Minnesota, and what steps need to be taken to address them. https://t.co/XylcHYqEvm

High-speed internet access isn’t a nice thing to have, it’s a necessary thing to have. Though we have made important progress on the #broadband front, too many Minnesotans—especially in rural, tribal, & low-income communities—still lack access to reliable & affordable broadband.

This morning I also met with Hibbing Fire Chief Erik Jankila to present him w/ a flag that was flown over the U.S. Capitol Building. This flag is in honor of Steve Gillitzer, a retired Hibbing Dept Captain who passed away while trying to save his family from a house fire in '17. https://t.co/oO580RfkB3

A great morning on the Range! Today I met with Iron Range steelworkers in Eveleth to talk about challenges facing the iron and steel industry. As Senator, I will fight to curb the illegal steel dumping that is hurting too many Northland communities. https://t.co/c1mA16z2YB

When I get back to Washington, I will make a full-court press on protecting people's pensions. We must ensure that Minnesota retirees, like the ones I met today, don’t have the rug pulled out from under them.

Today in Duluth I met with Sherman Liimatainen, Vice President of the National United Committee to Protect Pensions, and Central States Pension Fund retirees to talk about how we can fix this problem. https://t.co/ZeXPNUeIPs

After decades of hard work, Minnesotans who paid in to a good pension deserve to retire with the peace of mind that they won’t lose their hard-earned retirement. But right now, problems plaguing our nation’s pension system threaten to upend that promise.

Tonight I attended a reception to visit with Minnesotans in Duluth & hear what issues they care about. Thanks to everyone who joined me. I’ll be sharing what I've heard tonight with my colleagues in Washington because it’s my job to make sure MN voices are heard. https://t.co/JARqaWeA4E

Every time I travel across Minnesota, I feel incredible pride—in our communities and community leaders, in hard-working families, in farmers and businesses, and in all the women, men, and children who call our great state home.

Happy 90th Birthday to my friend Vice President Walter Mondale. Fritz – it was an honor to have you accompany me to my swearing-in ceremony. As Senator, I’m committed to upholding the progressive legacy set by leaders like you. https://t.co/A9Af0kac2x
As Senator, I’m going to lead the fight in tackling the #skillsgap to help strengthen our workforce, create more good-paying jobs, and maintain our country’s competitiveness.
